Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Bosnia and Herzegovina. The Bosnian authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus.
International travel
Current travel measures include forbidding entry at borders to foreign nationals travelling from Austria, Belgium, France, Germany, Italy, Iran, Japan, Romania, Spain, South Korea, Switzerland, and Hubei Province and the city of Wuhan in China. Everyone entering BiH is required to self-isolate for fourteen days. Those showing symptoms of the virus could find themselves detained in camps. New restrictions on travel may be introduced at short notice. You should comply with any additional screening measures put in place by the authorities.
Some airports remain open, although airline schedules are subject to constant change and withdrawal of services at short notice.
Some border crossing points into Bosnia and Herzegovina are closed and neighbouring countries have also placed restrictions on international travel. If you need further information about border crossing, the Border Police of Bosnia and Herzegovina are publishing updates. Please also check FCO travel advice for neighbouring countries.
Other measures
The Federation entity of BiH (including Sarajevo) announced a curfew from 1800 until 0500, effective 22 March until further notice, in addition to an existing curfew for those under the age of 18 and over the age of 65 to stay in their homes until 31 March. Republika Srpska announced a 2000 to 0500 curfew for all, and a 24 hour curfew for those over the age of 65, effective from 21 March until 30 March. Both entities of Bosnia and Herzegovina, the Federation (including Sarajevo) and Republika Srpska, have advised the temporary closure of educational institutions. Schools in Brcko District are closed indefinitely. In some parts of the country there are restrictions on the opening of shops, restaurants and other facilities. Other restrictive measures include closures of caf√©s, restaurants, gyms, spas, cinemas, theatres, and other facilities across the country, as well as a ban on all public gatherings. Food shops, pharmacies, and petrol stations will continue working. Further restrictions could be introduced without notice Keep up to date with information from your tour operator, transport or accommodation provider on the impact on any existing travel plans.
Further restrictions could be introduced without notice. Keep up to date with information from your tour operator, transport or accommodation provider on the impact on any existing travel plans.
Further information
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
